column4: Help
The family to which the taxon belongs.
The sub-family to which the taxon belongs (if indeed there is one).
The genus to which the taxon belongs.

If you know the sex, specify it here. This is different from the other characters specified in the knowledge base in that it is not used as an identification character on its own, but it can sometimes be used to provide context for some other values you supply (i.e. those that are sexually dimorphic).
The habitat niche in which the harvestman is found.
The species is closely associated with man.
The season in which the harvestman can be found.
column12: Paul Richard's FSC chart supplemented by viewing phenology on SRS website

column4: The months over which adults have been recorded for the Spider Recording Scheme (sourced 24/08/2017).
The month in which most adults have been recorded for the Spider Recording Scheme (sourced 24/08/2017).
The body length of the harvestman to the nearest 0.5 mm.
column12: Paul Richard's FSC chart and his spreadsheet

column4: Enter the body length of the harvestman in millimetres (estimate to the nearest half a millimetre). Note that this does NOT include the legs - enter the length of the body only.
The range of body lengths reasonable for males (in millimetres).
The range of body lengths reasonable for females (in millimetres).
Is the body dorso-ventrally flattened?
Does the body of the harvestman appear grannular and/or  have soil particles adhering?

Does the harvestman have a saddle? If so, how distinct? A 'saddle' is an area on the dorsal surface of the abdomen which is a more or less solid block of colour different from the rest of the abdomen.
Match the saddle shape to the closest description(s).
Indicate whether or not the saddle apears to be truncated, i.e. ends abruptly (on tergite 4 or 5).
Select the description(s) which best describe the markings on the saddle of the harvestman.
Indicate whether or not a central longitudinal stripe is present on the body.
Are transverse rows of tubercles present on the dorsal surface of the abdomen? This does not refer to tubercles around the head, edge of carapace or on the legs.
Do the ends of the dorsal tubercles increase in width to form swollen or flat-topped ends?
Indicate if any of these descriptions matches the dorsal tubercles.
Other noticeable dorsal markings not covered by other characters.

Some harvestmen have a trident, consisting of three tubercles projecting from the cephalothorax in front of the eyes (there may be additional tubercles). But there are many other types of head projection. Select the descriptions that best match projections at front of the head.
If a trident is present, select descriptions which best match its orientation. Note that there can be a great deal of variation in this character within a single species.
Select descriptions which best describe the relative lengths of the trident members (if present).

Select descriptions which best match arrangement of other tubercles around the trident (if present). In some species these tubercles can be the same size as some of those in the trident. In others, they can be much smaller. You will need to look very carefully with a hand lens.
Are there any distinctive features of the trident (if present)?
Are the eyes set on a raised ocularium?
Does there appear to be pale eye rings around the eyes on the ocularium?
Compare the relative length (along midline) and width (across eyes) of the ocularium and select the option that most closely matches.
Select the option that best describes the arrrangement of tubercles on the ocularium.
If the tubercles on the ocularium are arranged into two regular rows, indicate the number of tubercles in a single row.
Select the option that best describes the type of tubercles on the ocularium.
What type of armature (tubercles) does the ocularium have?
If the ocularium armature is of 'tubercle' type, how do the ends of the tubercles look?
How would you describe the size of the armature on the ocularium?
Are there any other noticeable features of the ocularium?

Is there a claw on the palp and, if so, is it smooth or toothed? (Note that this is not a character that you can use in the field - even with a hand lens. Microscopic examination is required to see whether or not the claw is toothed. If you can see a claw but not well enough to see whether or not it is toothed, e.g. with a hand lens, select both toothed and smooth options.)
Is the palpal tarsus longer or shorter than the tibia?
Indicate whether or not an apophysis (projection)  is visible on the palpal tibia and, if so, it's relative size.
Indicate whether or not an apophysis (projection) is visible on the palpal patella and, if so, it's relative size.
Indicate whether or not an apophysis (projection) is visible on the palpal femur and, if so, it's relative size.

Select the description that best match any spine-tipped tubercles on the ventral side of the palpal femur. This excludes any tubercles which are better described simply as weak spines, spicules or hairs.
Indicate whether or not all segments of the palps are covered in small knobbed hairs (i.e. hairs with swollen ends).
Are there any distinctive features of the palps?

Is there a spur underneath the basal segment of the chelicera? This is not really a useful field character and is normally only of any use for preserved specimens viewed under a microscopic (even then some dexterous manipulation of the cherlicerae is necessary to see it).
If there are visible projections on the chelicerae, select the description(s) which best matches them.
Are there any small projections just above the chelicerae, but below the dorsal surface of the body? (Technically, they arise from the supra-cheliceral lamellae.)

What's the length of the legs relative to the body of the harvestman. Select the value which best matches. (This character only makes sense if you are familiar with the range of relative leg lengths amongst the different species, but you will soon pick this up.)

column3: Length of legs 1 and 2 relative to body
column4: Are legs 1 & 2 longer or shorter than the length of the body?
What's the length of the second legs in millimetres? (Just one of them.)
Select the description(s) which best match the colour and markings of the legs. Select as many that apply.

Indicate if and how strongly legs appear to be annulated, i.e. ringed with contrasting light and dark pigment. This refers to more or less even areas of contrasting colour - do not interpret legs that change colour just at the very distal ends as annulated.
Indicate whether legs are the same basic colour as those on the body or if they are noticeably darker.
Select the description which best matches any markings present on the coxae (you may need to view the harvestman from underneath, but the markings can sometimes be seen from the side).
Select the description which best matches any notable markings present on the trochanters.
Are there any notable features of leg armature?

Describe the general armature on the femurs. This refers to rows, or a general covering, of tubercles over whole length of femurs and excludes spines confined to the end of the femurs (the subject of another character).

column3: Terminal spines on femurs and patellas
column4: Are there strong spines at the distal ends of, at least, the patellas and femurs?

column3: Shape of femurs in cross section
column4: Select the description when best matches the cross section shape of the femurs.

column3: Shape of patellas in cross section
column4: Select the description when best matches the cross section shape of the patellas.

column3: Shape of tibias in cross section
column4: Select the description when best matches the cross section shape of the tibias.
Are there any distinctive features of the legs?
